          "body": "Verses 22-23 are among the most transparent moments of prophetic intercession in the entire Old Testament. Moses returns to the LORD and says: 'O LORD, why have You brought harm to this people? Why did You ever send me? Ever since I came to Pharaoh to speak in Your name, he has done harm to this people, and You have not delivered Your people at all.' Three accusations are embedded in the lament: God caused harm, Pharaoh caused harm, and God has not kept His word. This is not apostasy; it is the prayer of a man whose theological framework is straining under the weight of observed reality. The same pattern appears in Habakkuk 1:2-3 ('How long, O LORD, will I call for help and You will not hear?'), in Jeremiah 20:7-9, and in the psalms of lament (Psalms 22, 44, 88). Keller notes that the lament psalms give the believer permission to bring the gap between God's promises and present reality directly to God rather than resolving it privately by abandoning faith. Moses does not walk away from Yahweh; he walks back to Yahweh with the problem. That is precisely what faithful prayer looks like in the dark."
